        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-08-31T14:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-08-31T14:57:00-05:00" n="261"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d261">
                <head>261. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Indonesia</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d261fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 756D.00/8–2657. Top Secret; Limited Distribution. Drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MJG1">Mein</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MR2">Murphy</persName>; approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MR2">Murphy</persName>; and cleared with <persName
                            corresp="#p_CHSJ1">Cumming</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JHP1"
                            >Howard P. Jones</persName>, and the Executive Secretariat. Repeated to
                        Kuala Lumpur for Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HCA1"
                            >Herter</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-08-31T15:57:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 31, 1957—3:57 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>474. Department appreciates considerations raised your 505,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d261fn2">
                        <ref target="#d255">Document 255</ref>.</note> but your statement that
                    Department’s position reflects “completely defeatist attitude” is gross
                    misinterpretation of Department’s thinking. Our concern is 1) that advantage may
                    be taken of conference by Communists or Army to arrest or eliminate leading
                    anti-Communist elements present Djakarta, and 2) that for lack of adequate
                    preparation conference may not succeed which would only strengthen hand of
                        <persName corresp="#p_Sukarno1">Sukarno</persName> and lead to further
                    disintegration of Indonesia to advantage of Communists. You should seek and
                    report as much information as possible concerning conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
